## Neo4j graph algorithms library

msg.data: Neo4j graph algorithms library

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Streaming betweenness centrality

The syntax we have had in graph algorithms library was `algo.betwenness.stream('Node label', 'Relationship type', {configuration map})`

msg.data:
Streaming betweenness centrality

The syntax we have had in graph algorithms library was algo.betwenness.stream('Node label', 'Relationship type', {configuration map})

paragraphs.text:
%neo4j_algo
CALL algo.betweenness.stream("User", "FOLLOWS")
YIELD nodeId, centrality
RETURN algo.getNodeById(nodeId).id  AS user, centrality
ORDER BY centrality DESC;

%md

As we can see in results, Alice is the main broker in this network, but Mark and
Doug aren’t far behind. In the smaller subgraph all shortest paths go through David,
so he is important for information flow among those nodes.

### Write-back betweenness centrality
If we want to store the results of the algorithm back to the graph, we can use the write-back version of the algorithm.

msg.data:
Write-back betweenness centrality

If we want to store the results of the algorithm back to the graph, we can use the write-back version of the algorithm.

paragraphs.text:
%neo4j_algo
CALL algo.betweenness('User', 'FOLLOWS', {writeProperty:'betweenness'});

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Approximate betweenness centrality

Recall that calculating the exact betweenness centrality on large graphs can be very
expensive. We could therefore choose to use an approximation algorithm that runs
much faster but still provides useful (albeit imprecise) information.

msg.data:
Approximate betweenness centrality

Recall that calculating the exact betweenness centrality on large graphs can be very
expensive. We could therefore choose to use an approximation algorithm that runs
much faster but still provides useful (albeit imprecise) information.

paragraphs.text:
%neo4j_algo
CALL algo.betweenness.sampled.stream("User", "FOLLOWS", {strategy:"degree"})
YIELD nodeId, centrality
RETURN algo.getNodeById(nodeId).id AS user, centrality
ORDER BY centrality DESC;

%md

Our top influencers are similar to before, although Mark now has a higher ranking
than Doug.
Due to the random nature of this algorithm, we may see different results each time
that we run it. On larger graphs this randomness will have less of an impact than it
does on our small sample graph.

## Neo4j graph data science library

msg.data: Neo4j graph data science library

paragraphs.text:
%md
The recommended way to use the GDS library is using the named graphs, where we first load the graph in memory and then proceed to run algorithms on it.

The syntax for creating named graphs is `CALL gds.graph.create(in-memory graph name, node label, relationship type)`.

msg.data:
The recommended way to use the GDS library is using the named graphs, where we first load the graph in memory and then proceed to run algorithms on it.

The syntax for creating named graphs is CALL gds.graph.create(in-memory graph name, node label, relationship type).

paragraphs.text:
%neo4j_gds
CALL gds.graph.create('betweenness_example', 'User', 'FOLLOWS');

### Streaming betweenness centrality
If we want to run the betweenness algorithm on the whole in-memory named graph, we don't have to specify any additional configuration. Other than that, the syntax is similar to that of the Graph algorithms library.

msg.data:
Streaming betweenness centrality

If we want to run the betweenness algorithm on the whole in-memory named graph, we don’t have to specify any additional configuration. Other than that, the syntax is similar to that of the Graph algorithms library.

paragraphs.text:
%neo4j_gds
CALL gds.alpha.betweenness.stream('betweenness_example') YIELD nodeId, centrality
RETURN gds.util.asNode(nodeId).id AS name, centrality ORDER BY centrality DESC LIMIT 10

### Write-back betweenness centrality

`WriteProperty` parameter defines the property of the node, where the results of the algorithm should be stored. If it is not defined, the results will not be stored in any property.
